,Recommended,263300,9115058,"Posted: 14 February, 2014",all,TheSprinkle42,"So, BlazBlue. Never played the actual game until now, but I had Bang, Tager, Rachel, Noel, and Ragna for MUGEN, so I was curious to see where they were from. How is the game? Surprisingly good for a 2D 1v1 fighter. I never got into games like Mortal Combat and Street Fighter because they didn't seem very interesting. You didn't know much about the characters, they all looked the same, and they just seemed like something you would just play at a friends house.(note that not all of these statements are neccessarily true, because I never did play them) BlazBlue, however, focuses on only twelve characters, which is small for a fighting game roster in this day and age. Because of this, they all look different, all use different tactics, and all play differently, with a few extreme examples. You've got Ragna, the all-rounder and face of the game, a man who wears a trenchcoat-shaped cliche and wields a big sword, Noel, who uses dual pistols which behave unlike most pistols I've seen, V-13, which is somehow pronounced 'Nu', who animates eight floating blades for attack and defense, and Taokaka, a cat-person with massive claws and some truly impressive speed. These all use the same controls and are usable by pretty much everyone to good effect. But then you've got Akumen and Rachel, who play completely differently. Add to this variety a story mode for each character, and you've got something I didn't expect from this genre. Other than the story mode, there's a versus mode, training mode, Arcade mode, Score attack, and that's it.The art design is consistently interesting, and all the stages are distinct from each other. Music is pretty good, but nothing standout. Gameplay wise, it's pretty balanced. A few characters have really powerful attacks that are balanced by their completely different playstyles, which lends the characters variety without making some of them overpowered.Overall, it's a fun game, and it's only ten bucks. I recommend it."
