,Recommended,263300,9738361,"Posted: 5 April, 2014",all,Animus Furandi,"BlazBlue: CT is a good fighting game that could have been a great if Arc System Works had only pushed the envelope a little more in terms of creativity. The visuals are nice, the controls are intuitive, and the extensive story mode makes for some entertaining reading. All of the fundamentals are in place. Nonetheless, Arcsys pushed this game out during a time when they legally couldn't make Guilty Gear games, and as a result, everything about this game smacks of a poor man's Guilty Gear. Anyone saying it isn't fair to compare the two series is delusional. Both games are the exact same flavor of fighter, but BlazBlue performs just a step below its sibling series in most regards. Every character on the roster is some transparent Bizarro World counterpart of someone from Guilty Gear. The music is the same metal style, but the melodies aren't as catchy aside from tunes that too closely resemble Guilty Gear pieces. The story is entertaining, but not as interesting. And the lack of online multiplayer in a PC port is a fault too glaring to omit. The overall gameplay, however, does manage to be on par with Arcsys's flagship fighter. Don't confuse my intentions; BlazBlue: CT is a good game in its own right. This brings me to my point: The developers didn't need to borrow so much from Guilty Gear. If you like the developer's other fighting offerings, you'll like this one, because it's almost the exact same thing. Arcsys would have done better to capitalize on the opportunity to create a more unique series, but instead, they came out with BlazBlue: Totally Not Guilty Gear, Sega."
