76561198011614926,Recommended,263300,9361708,"Posted: 6 March, 2014",all,Wily Westerner,"EDIT: Continuum Shift Extend is coming to Steam, and as is mentioned in the final paragraph, CSE has a condensed version of Calamity Trigger's story rendering Calamity Trigger obsolete. I am leaving this review up anyway, but CSE makes a better entry point into the series with Calamity Trigger being an additional purchase for those who want to experience the alternate routes.Blazblue features a great sci-fi story told via visual novel sections interspersed with the best 2D fighter gameplay I've ever experienced.The story takes place in a post-apocalyptic world in which society has already been rebuilt and futuristic tech that runs off magic has been developed. The lore is quite complicated, but most of it is explained in the non-canon ""Teach Me, Miss Litchi"" segments, which consist of light-hearted skits performed by super-deformed versions of the game's main characters. Having the lore explanations separate from the main game allows for the main storylines to move at a decent pace. However, in Calamity Trigger the ""Teach Me, Miss Litchi"" segments are unlocked as you play the game, so you may end up completely lost while playing the main story. As for tone, there is a serious story in the game that is told in a serious manner, but there is also an abundance of humour and gag routes in the series.The actual gameplay seems to cater to both hardcore competitive fighter fans and unskilled casual players (like me). Combos are easy to pull off and flow together well, all the special moves have simple inputs and can even be mapped to a single button/key/analogue stick flick, and the easy difficulty is rather easy. There's more that appeals to the hardcore crowd, but as this version lacks online play, said people are better off with the console version, which they would likely already own. I had a hard time with hard difficulty and some normal fights, so there may be a challenge to be had for those who want one, but not as much of a challenge as you could have against human players.The PC version seems to play just as well as the console versions, but lacks online play, so it's vs. computer and local play only. The included soundtrack features a lot of metal, but also has some symphonic rock. There are 42 tracks, but some short audio clips such as the ""[character] vs. [character]"" screen music is included, so it's more like 34 songs.Highly recommended, unless Continuum Shift Extend is an option, as that contains a condensed version of Calamity Trigger's story complete with most of the memorable fights as well as minor beneficial tweaks, the entirety of Continuum Shift, and a few extra story routes not found elsewhere."
