76561198113502915,Recommended,263300,9149780,"Posted: 16 February, 2014",all,Alteredgamer1056,"Okay, first things first. Blazblue is arguably my favorite fighting game ever. I've been a huge fan of the series since I first played this game on PS3. I currently own Blazblue Continuum Shift (EXTEND) on my PS Vita and it's one of my favorite games of all time. I am extremely excited to see this game released here on Steam!However, I must be honest. As much as I love this game, this is a extremely straightforward port of the console versions. A Gamepad is a MUST to enjoy this game properly, as keyboard and mouse controls just don't work for fighting games of this sort. I am admittendly disappointed by the lack of online multiplayer. However, this version of the game does still support local co-op play. Perhaps even more impressive is the inclusion of the GAMES ORIGINAL SOUNDTRACK which is included with this Steam release. As Blazblue has one of the most impressive soundtracks in any video game, fighting or otherwise, this alone pretty much justifies the purchase unless you can track down the fairly elusive CD.Blazblue is a traditional 2D Japanese fighting game with a emphasis on fast, dynamic combat and tactical strategy. The fighting is extremely dependent on precise timing and mastery of skills. There are several difficulty levels ranging from 'casual' to 'nightmarishly hard', and this allows players of all skill levels to jump in and enjoy playing the game. There is also a in-depth training mode which will walk you through each character's moveset and learn basic gameplay mechanics.In addition, there is also a standard 'Arcade mode' in which you fight increasingly difficult opponents to win. A 'Story mode' which takes each character through their own unique storyline, and a 'verses' mode where you can challenge your friends in local co-op matches.Blazblue: Calamity Trigger is a fantasic game and worthy of anyone's gaming collection. I recommend buying this edition if only for the elusive Offical soundtrack and it's a decent port of the console versions.Highly recommended! (Unless you own one of the console versions...)"
