,Recommended,263300,10706067,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,Fries,"Recommended to show support for ArcSys fighting games for PC. (More Guilty Gear, BlazBlue, and maybe Persona4Arena PC?)Essentially the GFWL version now without GFWL, the Steam version now lacks Online and apparently still suffers from the same issues.Being the first entry of the series, Calamity Trigger is a bit simpler than the other combo heavier sequels and revisions (characters being given more move set options) but all 3 main entries in the series try different balance mechanics that make them play a bit different. With Dashes, a Parry system, Barrier blocking, a simple ""revolver"" combo system (A > B > C > D move links) and Cancel options, the pacing can get pretty hectic in BlazBlue.Aside from the PC versions (Steam and Windows 8 Store), I've only played the PSP version of Calamity Trigger and the Steam version appears to be a port of the home console versions meaning that it lacks the addition of Legion mode from the PSP port and the BlayzBloo Shop (there are still unlocks from the shop available.)If you don't mind having to restart your PC to get rid of the framerate issue that appears after a while of PC uptime (fps sinks to a capped 30) every time, the PC versions of the BlazBlue games have almost instant loading times for matches (you can skip the matchup screens not long after they pop up) which make them my preferred versions, having played the latest 2 installed on the PS3.The included OST appears to be the one from the console's US Limited Edition as 320kbit mp3 files."
,Recommended,263300,10010726,"Posted: 3 May, 2014",all,CTCGod,"There are two things I like about Arc System Works (who made Guilty Gear and Persona 4 Arena): all of the bgm in their work is kick♥♥♥♥♥ and their games are so good that I actually postpone reviewing them to play them more, much like BlazBlue: Calamity Trigger.BlazBlue: Calamity Trigger is the first installment of Arc System Works' BlazBlue series. Taking Place in the 13th hierarchical city of Kagutsuchi, Calamity Trigger displays the city after six legendary heroes defeated the infamous ""Black Beast."" Ever since then, the Novus Orbis Librarium (a.k.a the NOL or the Library) has governed Kagutsuchi. Soon afterwards, the village of Ikaruga openly rebelled and was quickly destroyed. Now the Library rules with a tight grip, punishing anyone who defies them with death. Although it doesn't really explain it in the opening cutscene to story mode, Arc System Works made Kagutsuchi feel like an oppressed city through the backgrounds showing guards locking down certain stages, to even some of the characters who work for the NOL. Much other than that, BlazBlue focuses less on the big picture and more on the interactions between characters and their complicated relationships.BlazBlue is an absolutely gorgeous game, each hand drawn sprite looks great and is animated spectacularly. The character backgrounds also play off of the characters backstories and reflects them through the stages, like Taokaka, who comes from a poor village of cat-like people. On her stage, you can see members of her village chasing chickens around trying to eat them. All of the characters special moves, distortion drives, and astral heats are smooth and stylish.As if the story and graphics don't appease to me enough, the flashy yet simple combat system made me feel like a bad♥♥♥♥♥in no time. Playing off the revolver system (attacks go from weak to strong), BlazBlue: Calamity Trigger s simple enough to pick up and start doing combos yet complex enough for seasoned vets to dish out some real damage. The crux of Calamity Trigger's play style and one best parts of the game is the ""Drive"" system. In a nutshell, no to characters play alike. Ragna the Bloodedge's drive Soul Eater steals health from the opponent and adds it to his own if he sustained damage. Jin's Frostbite freezes opponents on the spot, allowing for devastating combos. Arc also did a great job balancing out the characters. Now Tager, a beefy character with a large hitbox and no double jump or dash, can have a chance with his high damage output against Taokaka, one of the fastest characters in the game and deals a small amount of damage. The only thing I don't like, however, is when they ported Calamity Trigger to Steam, something happened and there is no online multiplayer, meaning you'll have to be sitting next to your friend to fight him.Verdict:+Beautiful graphics+addictive gameplay+Awesome Soundtrack+Balanced Roster-No Online Multiplayer9.5 OutstandingEven if Calamity Trigger isn't your favorite BlazBlue title, it is still fun plus you get the soundtrack to boot. Hopefully in the future, if it's successfull enough, Arc System Works will put Continuum Shift and Chronophantasmna on Steam as well (with online capability too). If you are a fan of Guilty Gear/P4A or just want to try a new type of fighting game, then do yourself a favor and buy BlazBlue: Calamity Trigger."
