76561198247560826,Recommended,263300,19705039,"Posted: 14 December, 2015",all,TransomAndMask,"Here it begins.This is one of the (fully voiced) visual novel mashup games that alongside the Persona series forms the foundation for how I measure such things. It's also the first fighter of its format that I got any good at. The story is a gorgeous incompressible fractal, the character design is full of strong aesthetic persona that pushes all my buttons, and the mechanics are so good that lesser games such as the Street Fighter series are now unplayable to me.The way the input buffer is built allows you to jam on a button and then overwrite the input if you change your mind before the attack actually launches, provided you're fast enough. In that way it plays more like Soul Calibur and less like Mortal Kombat. That input buffer is the biggest deciding factor in whether I buy a fighting game now. The quick-sticking system is also a godsend to new players: push the analog stick in one of the up or right to do a character-specific special move, left to do a super move, and down to do a finisher after you unlock them. This is a system that should be in all fighting games.Also a part of the Brawl Minus school of gameplay balance: when every character is OP, no one is. Each character breaks the rules of the game in their own unique way from Tao's directional air dashes to Hakumen's counter button and autocharging specials to Nu 13's intangible-dash cancels and ability to attack anywhere on the screen if you're precise enough.Pro tip tho: don't rely on integrated graphics to play it. My laptop chugs a bit, and as a very technical player this can throw me off considerably in more intense matches. That or I've gotten so fast that I need a new controller, because I'm inputting moves faster than the analog stick's sample rate.The franchise is part of my Platinum Collection. On PS3/360 I've put over 2k hours combined into this series, and now I get to buy them all over again on Steam.Hurry up and release Chrono Phantasma: Extend on Steam so I can buy that too."
