76561198114730270,Recommended,263300,13485376,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,MrExtravagant,"I purchased this a while back, in order to introduce me to the BlazBlue franchise that I've heard about for a while now, and let me tell you, this game surpassed my expectations.This game is grand. The visuals are spectaclarly detailed. The voice acting is, overall, wonderful, with only a couple of flat performances. The narritive is rich, detailed, and shrouded in so much mystery, you won't be able to put it down until you know everything there is to know about BB:CT. And most importantly, the gameplay is fantastic; surprisingly smooth and even, and set at just the right pace.There isn't much wrong in this game, other than a few nit-picky things that are purely my opinion, but I'm pretty sure that someone out there agrees with me. Firstly, the voice acting can get a little flat. I mean, it isn't something that's going to distract you too much, as the characters with the flat acting only appear once or twice in the story mode, and there are far from important to the plot (they aren't even named so I have no clue why I'm complaining - _ -'), but it's just a little thing I noticed. Another thing is how many cliff-hangers there are in the story. I know, I know, that's like saying that I don't want a sequel, and that I don't like the mystery, which I do; but still, they could at least wrap up a few things. I won't give any spoilers, in case someone reading this hasn't played the game, but it left me hungry for more, and if the sequels follow this example, leaving me in the dark until either the next installment is ported to Steam or newly released to the masses (which, from the looks of it, could take a while), then I'll go insane trying to formulate theories for what happens.Despite my nit-picks, BlazBlue: Calamity Trigger is one awesome game. Take it from a new fan who's downloading the sequel as he types; if you haven't played this game, you really should."
